But in practice, all of my analyses are multiple CPU years on a cluster.

00:47:52.239 --> 00:47:53.439
Yep, yep, yep, yep, yep, yep.

00:47:53.439 --> 00:47:54.719
So, how does that work?

00:47:54.719 --> 00:47:57.600
Yep, yep. Two, there's three answers to that.

00:47:58.320 --> 00:48:04.879
So, one, I didn't talk about, there's a feature of Cordo called Freeze, which basically says,

00:48:04.879 --> 00:48:10.159
serialize all the outputs of the computations, and then you can bring them back.

00:48:10.159 --> 00:48:13.840
So, you could re-render the document, and as long as the document hasn't changed,

00:48:13.840 --> 00:48:18.080
it's gonna bring those back. So, that allows you to sort of go across

00:48:18.080 --> 00:48:22.000
time and space and not have to re-render everything. So, Freeze is one answer.

00:48:22.000 --> 00:48:24.800
And that's where you actually, with Freeze, you actually check in those

00:48:25.760 --> 00:48:28.719
outputs into version control. They become part of the project.

00:48:29.600 --> 00:48:36.239
The other answers are caching-oriented, and one cache is, Jupyter Notebook is a cache,

00:48:36.239 --> 00:48:39.840
and so that's one way to do it. I put it in a Jupyter Notebook, I'm not gonna re-render it,

00:48:39.840 --> 00:48:42.239
and I can just reference it, as I showed in the last piece.

00:48:43.040 --> 00:48:46.800
And then there are, as you probably experimented with, there's like Knitter Cache and Jupyter

00:48:46.800 --> 00:48:49.679
Cache and things like that. So, there's a few different ways to do it,

00:48:50.399 --> 00:48:56.879
but it really has to do with just making sure that, at that time of that expensive render,

00:48:56.879 --> 00:49:00.159
that the appropriate thing is serialized, so that it can always be brought back without

00:49:00.159 --> 00:49:05.040
requiring a re-render. So, we're gonna have to do a big transition,

